e in to final yes list.</p> <p>For any more questions, our phone lines are open.</p> <p><i><b>Direct numbers :</b> </i>Contact : Vamsi 9700212029</p> '),(475,'1450265260000','New Year Ride To Bidar Fort on 2nd Jan 2016','227452725','1451903019000','https://www.meetup.com/Theclimbon/events/227452725/','Call Vamsi 9700212029, rohith 9676722155','2016-01-02 06:00:00.000000','past',' (B.H.E.L check post)','Hyderabad','in','Lingampally',0,'2016-01-04 10:23:00.000000','<p><b>Lets start the new year with a day trip</b></p> <p>Bidar is a city in the Indian state of Karnataka. It is also called as crown of Karnataka. Bidar city is known for its<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bidri_ware\">Bidri</a> <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicraft\">handicraft</a> products. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manjira_River\">Manjira River</a> is one of the main rivers supplying drinking water to Bidar. Bidar is a charming district- one of its charms being a very bracing climate practically throughout the district and for the greater part of the year.</p> <p>Bidar has lots of historical monuments from the Bahmani era. The structure of the great Mahmud Gawan Arabic University is reminiscent of the rich architecture of the Bahmani era. The<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bidar_Fort\">Bidar Fort</a> situated next to the city is one of the biggest forts in India</p> <p>Places to visit in Bidar</p> <p><b>Bidar Fort: </b>The Bidar Fort in Karnataka is a beautiful creation of the then ruler of Karnataka which is surrounded by a triple-moated wall. It is constructed out of red rock and had an intricate battlement and a baronial gateway. If you ever visit the Fort, you will get to see the crumbling ruins of the bastions and gates. Other features of the Bidar Fort at Karnataka are the royal baths and spacious kitchens, a large audience hall and wide pleasure-pavilions, all in a state of ruin. But this grand edifice still stands the ravages of time as a silent tribute to the past glory of the Bidar Kingdom.</p> <p><img src=\"http://photos2.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/4/9/0/1/600_445158689.jpeg\" /></p> <p><img src=\"http://photos2.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/a/4/1/c/600_266622012.jpeg\" /></p> <p><b>Rangeen Mahal</b>: The Rang Mahal of the Bidar Fort of Karnataka has intricately carved beautiful wooden pillars. You will be amazed to see the wonderful tiles that are engraved with Persian couplets. The exquisite mother-of-pearl inlay work in the Bidar Fort is really worth seeing. There is a Madrassa of Khwaja Mahamud Gawan adjacent to it. The madrassa is an Islamic seminary constructed by the prime minister of the Bahmani court, Khwaja Mahamud Gawan. We will try to get permission to see this but is not guaranteed.</p> <p><img src=\"http://photos2.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/4/a/2/d/600_445158989.jpeg\" /></p> <p><b>Narasimha Jhira Cave Temple</b>: Narasimha Swami Temple is known to be a Sacred Temple for a Hindu devotee. This water cave temple virtually runs into a cave with water measuring 300 meters. The temple is a powerful deity of Lord Narasimha as per the belief<br/>where one has to wade through water up to chest height to have darshan of the idol. It’s a thrilling experience to travel through the cave as there is<br/>natural water within it. The bats and owls sitting on the roof top of cave are harmless to the devotees. The place is surrounded by picturesque valley.</p> <p><img src=\"http://photos4.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/a/6/3/8/600_266622552.jpeg\" /></p> <p><b>Gurudwara Nanak Jhira Sahib</b>: Gurudwara Nanak Jhira Sahib, which was built in the year 1948 and, is dedicated to the first Sikh Guru Nanak Dev Ji. The gurudwara comprises of Darbar Sahib, Diwan Hall and Langar Hall. In the Sukhaasan Room, Guru Granth Sahib, the holy book of Sikh, has been placed. Opposite to the front stairs of the gurudwara, there is a holy water tank. It is believed that a holy dip in the tank is enough to cleanse the body and soul, of the devotee of all the sins.</p> <p><img src=\"http://photos2.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/a/6/9/2/600_266622642.jpeg\" /></p> <p>Itinerary:</p> <p>6:00am: Meetup at BHEL Gate Lingampally</p> <p>Start towards Bidar by nh9</p> <p>7:00am Break for breakfast on the way</p> <p>10:30am Reach bidar fort and explore then continue to other places mentioned above and few more in bidar till 5pm</p> <p>5:00pm start back to Hyderabad</p> <p>9:00pm Tata Bye Bye</p> <p>What to wear:</p> <p>Wear Shoes</p> <p>• Wear any dress comfortable to you</p> <p>• One extra pair of dress because in narasimhaswami temple we have to go in water for darshan.</p> <p>• Towel</p> <p>• As we will be starting early, wear something to keep you warm.</p> <p>• What to bring:</p> <p>• Water bottles - 2 x 1 litres</p> <p>• Hat or cap as it will be hot afternoons</p> <p>• Electrol or glucose</p> <p>• Camera</p> <p>• Any medications physician prescribed</p> <p>• Loads of energy.</p> <p>Costs : Rs 150 Towards Club fund</p> <p>Guidelines: This is a historical place . No venturing towards steep cliff drops .</p> <p>Contact : Vamsi 9700212029, Rohith 9676722155</p> <p>Difficulty : Easy</p> <p>Transport: Personal Vehicles If possible there will be pool and petrol cost will be shared</p> <p>PLEASE ANSWER ALL THE QUESTIONS. IF YOU DO NOT WE WILL NOT BE ABLE TO WAIT FOR YOU AND YOUR RSVP WILL BE CONSIDERED VOID.</p> '),(476,'1448361605000','Enjoy the Beauty of Mallela Theertham on 3rd Jan Sunday','226987929','1452091656000','https://www.meetup.com/Theclimbon/events/226987929/','www.meetup.com/thecoh','2016-01-03 04:30:00.000000','past','Srisailam Highway','Andhra Pradesh','in','Mallela theertham',0,'2016-01-06 14:47:00.000000','<p><b>Mallela Theertham</b> is a Waterfall located in the Nallamala Forest in Telangana, India. The River Krishna flows through this forest. It is located <b>195 km</b> from Hyderabad.</p> <p><img src=\"http://photos3.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/8/f/5/600_436022293.jpeg\" /></p> <p><b>Wh